  }
}
group default_ip6 {
  router-id 192.168.248.199;
  local-address 2a00:abcd:8001:1::199;
  local-as 65001;
  hold-time 10;
  capability {
    route-refresh enable;
  }
  family {
    ipv6 unicast;
  }
  process add-routes6 {
    run /usr/bin/ruby /opt/announce_dns_bgp.rb --timeout=3 --announce='2a00:abcd:8000::230/128;2a00:abcd:8000::231/128;' --fqdns='www.google.com;www.google.ch;www.github.com;';
  }
  # IP6 rtr2_dcs
  neighbor 2a00:abcd::2 {
    group-updates true;
    description "IP6_rtr2_dcs";
    peer-as 65002;
  }
}
```

version:
```

ExaBGP : 3.4.16
Python : 2.7.6 (default, Jun 22 2015, 17:58:13)  [GCC 4.8.2]
Uname  : #42~14.04.1-Ubuntu SMP Fri May 13 17:27:22 UTC 2016
```

when I turn up logging I can see, that exabgp tries to announce ipv6 routes to ipv4 peers. 
other prefixes / IPs here but this is the log from my test system:
```
Route added to neighbor 2a0c:380:1001::242 local-ip 2a0c:380:1001::123 local-as 65001 peer-as 65530 router-id 192.168.216.123 family-allowed in-open : 5.34.248.231/32 next-hop 2a0c:380:1001::123
Wed, 01 Jun 2016 09:41:38 | INFO     | 4735   | reactor       | Route added to neighbor 2a0c:380:1001::242 local-ip 2a0c:380:1001::123 local-as 65001 peer-as 65530 router-id 192.168.216.123 family-allowed in-open, neighbor 192.168.216.242 local-ip 192.168.216.123 local-as 65001 peer-as 65530 router-id 192.168.216.123 family-allowed in-open : 192.168.248.231/32 next-hop 192.168.216.123
```
but I think I clearly separated this with the groups, right? 

is this a bug or am I doing something wrong?

thanks you, best regards
Marco

I'm running into a weird issue where searching a given type of document through `elasticsearch-py` that works ceases to work after I perform a search to a different document type.

I've taken both queries and execute them on ES through kibana and the problem doesn't seem to be happening on ES side I think it's more in the `elasticsearch-py` layer.

I was reading the documentation and it states that there's a connection pool for `urllib3` so instead of instanciating the `Elasticsearch()` client every time I needed I moved it to a shared location for re-use but this proved to be unsuccessful, I'm running out of ideas to debug this issue and it completely breaks my software.

Here's an example of the code I use to search


```
es = Elasticsearch([ELASTICSEARCH_HOST])
query = {
    "query": 
    {
        "bool": 
        {
            "must": 
            {
                "match": 
                {
                    "autocomp_field": 
                    {
                        "operator": "and",
                        "query": "Nancy"
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    },
    "from": 0,
    "size": 10
}

results = es.search(
        index="myindex",
        doc_type="model1",
        body=query
    )
```

however if I repeat this code with a different query such as 


```
es = Elasticsearch([ELASTICSEARCH_HOST])
query = {
    "query": 
    {
        "bool": 
        {
            "filter": [
                {
                    "term": 
                    {
                        "assets.Asset.assigned_user_id": 19
                    }
                }
            ],
            "must": 
            {
                "match": 
                {
                    "autocomp_field": 
                    {
                        "operator": "and",
                        "query": "apple"
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    },
    "from": 0,
    "size": 10
}

results = es.search(
        index="myindex",
        doc_type="model2",
        body=query
    )
```

the first search wont work ever again until I restart my python application (django btw)

the `autocomp_field` uses a custom analyzer however I've queried ES through kibana and it works every time so I don't think the problem is there

Currently at: https://github.com/marshmallow-code/marshmallow/blob/1781e9a18895aa9b473fb5587de3cf922416733e/marshmallow/schema.py#L397, iteration behavior is determined by list(). Would it be considered a useful feature to be able to override this behavior with a function that takes the object and returns an iterator? (similar to the way _serializer can be overriden)
‘’’python
def _dumper(obj):
    return (i for i in obj)
‘’’

[`import_string`](https://github.com/graphql-python/graphene/blob/d594a0eca86102ce2ebf9633018437eef8997f42/graphene/utils/module_loading.py#L5) works well. Unfortunately, [`get_type`](https://github.com/graphql-python/graphene/blob/0b92d3dba64f438e97a955d13f2ec542705d1e5e/graphene/types/utils.py#L43) doesn't take advantage of it's ability to accept a second argument, `dotted_attributes`.

The consequence of this is that users are unable to nest ObjectTypes inside a class – say, as an attribute.

In my case, this means that the dynamically generated InputObjectTypes must also be injected into the module namespace, which is poor behavior.

Looking at [`types.Argument`](https://github.com/graphql-python/graphene/blob/ab5a11b3993ae1dac1b8bef7974703c922b3a168/graphene/types/argument.py) it might seem that this functionality was omitted as it's difficult to implement.

However, an acceptable solution might be to modify `get_type` to look something like this:
```
class LazyType:
    def __init__(self, dotted_path, dotted_attributes=None):
        self.dotted_path = dotted_path
        self.dotted_attributes = dotted_attributes

def get_type(_type):
    if isinstance(_type, LazyType):
        return import_string(_type.dotted_path, _type.dotted_attributes)
    if isinstance(_type, string_types):
        return import_string(_type)
    if inspect.isfunction(_type) or isinstance(_type, partial):
        return _type()
return _type
```

